{
"content_id": "REALIA:11.6.2.5",
"reference_id": "REALIA:11.6.2.5",
"version": "1.0.4",
"title": "Denarius",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "11.6.2.5",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:11.6.2.5\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">11.6.2.5</span> Denarius</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">δηνάριον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(dēnarion)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt18:28\">MAT 18:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt20:2\">MAT 20:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt20:9\">MAT 20:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt20:10\">MAT 20:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt20:13\">MAT 20:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt22:19\">MAT 22:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark6:37\">MRK 6:37</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark12:15\">MRK 12:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:5\">MRK 14:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke7:41\">LUK 7:41</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke10:35\">LUK 10:35</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke20:24\">LUK 20:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John6:7\">JHN 6:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John12:5\">JHN 12:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev6:6\">REV 6:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev6:6\">REV 6:6</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/UBS-0001_denarius.jpg\" alt=\"The head of Emperor Tiberius on a denarius\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">The head of Emperor Tiberius on a denarius (© Kwo-Wei Peng by United Bible Societies)</figcaption></figure>Because of the recent rapid inflation in the world and the considerable loss of buying power of coinage metals such as gold, silver and copper in comparison to ancient times, a number of translators have attempted in some measure to relate coinage to buying power, or perhaps better, to earning power. Thus, rather than translating “denarius” by some specific amount in a modern currency, it may be equated to a day’s wage. For example, in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark6:37\">MRK 6:37</a> the literal expression “two hundred denarii” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>) is sometimes rendered “the equivalent of 200 days’ wages” or even “eight months of a laborer’s wages.” This will be a good solution in most cases with a couple of exceptions: (1) There are some passages where converting to work days will be unwieldy; for example, in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt18:28\">MAT 18:28</a> the debt of the second servant is equivalent to about four months’ wages, which is a figure that people can grasp. However, the debt of the first servant was approximately equivalent to the wages of 1000 men for 20 years. It would be awkward to include this in translation. (2) There are still some cultures in the world where hiring day laborers is unknown because each person or family unit in the village does its own hunting and gathering or even farming. In such cultures “a day’s wage” may have little meaning.</p>\n<p>When calculating the number of days’ wages, translators should not forget that, unlike other peoples in the ancient world, Jews did not work one day out of seven. Thus a work week consisted of six work days, and about 25 days made up one work month. The 100 denarii of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt18:28\">MAT 18:28</a> equaled four months’ salary and not three months, as stated in some common-language translations.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
